COVID-19 Data Analysis
Project 3 - SYNTECXHUB Data Science Internship

What this project does
I worked with the Johns Hopkins COVID-19 dataset to look at how cases changed over time for a few countries. The script cleans the data, calculates daily and weekly trends, and plots comparisons so you can see the differences at a glance.

Data used
The data comes directly from the public Johns Hopkins GitHub repo. It has daily confirmed cases for every country since early 2020.

Tools
Python, Pandas for handling the data, Matplotlib and Seaborn for the charts. Nothing fancy, just the standard stuff for data analysis.

What the code does
1. Downloads and reshapes the raw data so it’s easier to work with
2. Groups it by country and calculates daily new cases
3. Creates a 7-day rolling average to smooth out spikes
4. Plots total cases and rolling averages for US, India, Brazil, Pakistan, and Italy
5. Finds the day with the highest daily cases for each country
6. Gives a basic idea of whether cases are rising or falling in the last 2 weeks
7. Saves the charts and a couple of CSV summaries

Files you get after running
- total_cases_comparison.png: chart of total cases over time
- rolling_avg_comparison.png: chart of 7-day average daily cases  
- peak_cases_summary.csv: peak daily cases for each country
- r0_estimate.csv: simple trend estimate for the last 14 days
